This particular form has smaller spores, that match my measurements.

results.notes: This mass of fungi was collected by one of our members at the Bald Pate foray. The closest tree was an oak but it was a mixed hardwood forest. It has been extremely dry (a month and half without a good rain). There was a light brief rain the night before the foray. At first these looked like Craterellus but there were real gills, not ribs. Arrhenia seemed to fit the bill until I looked at the spores. They were odd shaped with many having an oil drop. The closest I could find was Clitopilopsis but I could only find a description of one in conifers or one in moss, this was growing on a mass of rotten wood and duff. The caps were 1 and 1.5cm, funnel shaped, grey- brown. The stipe 1.5-2cm long with the decurrent gills going halfway down the stipe. The stipe was the same color as the cap with white mycelleum at the base which glued the fruiting bodies to the duff/rotten wood. There were short gills inbetween the decurrent gills.

results.notes:
Found growing on a sloped lawn on the downslope side of ground-mounted solar panels. The only trees in this area are where a wooded area borders the lawn behind the panels. Before the panels were installed (2013) the 10-20 square yard area of sloped lawn was the primary location for multiple annual fruitings of A. rooseveltensis. After the panels were installed, this same species disappeared from the sloped lawn but then began to appear on a different part of the lawn; still about 10 yards or so from the wooded area bordering the lawn. Last year the A. rooseveltensis fruitings moved closer to where the panels are. So, it seems that the mycelium may have been initially disturbed, but has since been repopulating the area in front of the panels.
I think the primary associate for this amanita is a large shagbark hickory tree (probably 80-100 years old). But, there are several 15-25 foot tall red oaks closer to the mounted panels. These oak trees have mainly sprung up during the 21 years that I have lived here. My guess is the oaks have acquired the A. rooseveltensis form the hickory, and are now helping to spread the fruit bodies back onto the sloped lawn in front of the panels.
I placed a slide beneath the gills, in situ. Collected enough spores to see that a significant percentage qualify as broadly ellipsoid to ellipsoid, which verifies the A. rooseveltensis proposal.

results.notes: Jason H handed me this tiny mushroom on a green dried-up leaf. I thought it was some sort of Marasimius since it revived in water. It only had 6 gills and they were too small to take a piece of, so I smashed the whole thing under a cover slip. The spores looked globose but one side seemed to be flattened and the whole spore was covered with minute spines. After looking at the Largent book, the closest I could come to was Fayodia but that genus seems to have more than 6 gills with no short gills. The spores measured 10-11, so pretty big. The largest cream colored cap was 1mm across with scalloped edges. The stipe is the same color under the cap but then it darkend to almost black.

results.notes:
Inocybe tigrina
Sesimbra. Janeiro, 2021.

Espécie comum por quase toda a Europa, tem aqui o seu primeiro registo de uma frutificação em Portugal.
É uma espécie conhecida pela sua cutícula gretada radialmente (ou “tigrada”), algo que nem sempre acontece em todas as coleções. De aspeto e ecologia muito variada. Ocorre em Portugal de Norte a Sul do país, associada tanto a folhosas, coníferas como exclusivamente a Cistaceae (como pude comprovar com outras coleções).

Para além da macromorfologia, caracteriza-se principalmente pelos cistídios de longos pescoços, frequentemente ondulados e de paredes bem reativas ao hidróxido de potássio.
Tinha até há bem pouco tempo estatuto debatível, é agora reconhecida como espécie boa, parecida mas distinta de I. flocculosa (https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11557-021-01712-w).

Photos labeled A and B show fruit bodies growing on different areas of the same log. The bark on the log was partially intact and I thought it to be a beech log. But, having observed the spores at 400x, the fungus is not Tremella mesenterica (which I had surmised based upon the wood being “beech”). Genus Dacrymyces strongly suggests the wood was conifer. Possibly a white pine branch?
Spore print yellow.
Spores multiseptate (not observable in the photos); maximum lengths (on specimen A) approaching 30 microns. This maximum length significantly exceeds what is reported for D. chrysospermus. But the only other Dacrymyces species I know that has spores longer than D. chrysospermus is D. variisporus, which forms small circular “gumdrop” type fruit bodies.
This one is a bit of a mystery. At least for now, I’m calling it D. chrysospermus.

- Nearly spherical spores (Me = 9.8 × 9.4 µm ; Qe = 1)
- No significant graying observed on either side of volva, only very slight yellowish with aging. Not too thick, rather membranous (or just soggy/not at prime), but resistant. Cortical parts made of mostly filamentous hyphae running parallel to stipe and rare sphaerocysts and physaloid elements; medullar part made of ‘more numerous’ sphaerocysts (but still very few), tightly imbedded in dense network of hyphae running in all directions.

- Hymenial trama irregular to subdivergent, made of inlfated cells, sphaerocyst-like and physaloid, tightly wrapped by numerous filamentous hyphae in all directions. By the subhymenium some slender fusoid hyphae sometimes curve and branch towards hymenium, giving subdiverging appearance.

results.notes:
Fruiting beneath Coast Redwood(Sequoia sempervirens).
This is another interesting specimen at this location with a distinctly bulbous, abruptly bulbous stem base(similar to Agaricus smithii).
Cap: scales are few and far between, scant compared to average A. augustus collections.
Cap is also very thin, less robust in context than average A. augustus collections.
Veil adhering to cap margin and stem(splitting/not separating cleanly).
Odor: marzipan, almond extract.
I’m calling this Agaricus augustus group do to the interesting morphology(bulbous stem base, less scaly cap). Wrong time of year and wrong tree associate for A. smithii. May turn out to be interesting genetically.
I’m including a suggestion/vote as “could be” for Agaricus smithii in addition to outweighing label of “I’d call it that” Agaricus augustus group for this observation.
